        <div class="doc-content">
            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    Day 5 was about serving static files in Express and understanding how JavaScript modules work.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We looked at how to structure frontend files properly and how to import/export code both in Node.js and in the browser.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Serving Static Files in Express</h2>
                <p>
                    When building web apps with Express, frontend files like HTML, CSS,
                    and JavaScript need to be accessible to the browser.
                    This is done by telling Express which folder it should serve these files from. 
                </p>
                <p>Example configuration:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
import express from 'express';

const app = express();

app.use(express.static('public'));
                </code></pre>

                <p>The <code>express.static()</code> middleware allows Express to serve files directly from a specified directory.</p>

                <p>In this case, the <code>public</code> folder contains all client-side resources such as:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>HTML files</li>
                    <li>CSS files</li>
                    <li>JavaScript files</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    When a browser requests a file, Express looks for it inside the <code>public</code> directory
                    and serves it automatically (if it exists).
                </p>

                <h3>Why This Matters</h3>
                <p>
                    Instead of exposing the whole project, we only expose the <code>public</code> folder.
                    This helps avoid accidentally exposing server-side code.
                </p>

                <h3>Using <code>path.resolve()</code> in ES Modules</h3>
                <p>
                    When using ES Modules in Node.js, the global variable <code>__dirname</code> is not available.
                    This variable is part of the older CommonJS module system.
                </p>
            
                <p>Because of this, we use <code>path.resolve()</code> to construct the correct file path when sending files with Express.</p>

                <p>Example:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
import path from "path";

app.get("/", (req, res) => {
    res.sendFile(path.resolve("public/frontpage/frontpage.html"));
});
                </code></pre>

                <p><code>path.resolve()</code> converts the relative path into an absolute path, which is required when using <code>res.sendFile()</code>.</p>

                <p>Example of a project structure:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-bash">
├── public/
│   ├── frontpage/
│   │   ├── frontpage.html
│   │   ├── frontpage.css
|   |   └── frontpage.js
│   └── cookieFactory/
├── util/
│   └── esModuleCookiesUtil.js
├── package.json
└── app.js            
            </code></pre>
            <ul>
                <li>Only the files inside public can be accessed by the browser</li>
                <li>Files outside this folder, such as server-side logic or utility files, remain protected and cannot be requested directly from the client</li>
                <li>This separation helps avoid accidentally exposing server code</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Working with Modules in Node.js</h2>
                <p>Node.js has two module systems:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>CommonJS (older)</li>
                    <li>ES Modules (modern)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Both allow JavaScript files to share code with each other.</p>

                <h3>CommonJS</h3>
                <p>
                    Up until today, we have used CommonJS to share code between files,
                    and this was the default module system used in Node.js for many years before ES Modules were introduced.
                </p>
                <p>It uses:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>require()</code> to import code</li>
                    <li><code>module.exports</code> to export code</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>Exporting in CommonJS</h4>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const cookie = require("./cookie.json");

function getCookie() {
    return cookie;
}

module.exports = { getCookie };
                </code></pre>

                <h4>Importing in CommonJS</h4>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const cookiesUtil = require('./util/commonjsCookiesUtil.js');
                </code></pre>

                <h3>ES Modules (Modern JavaScript Modules)</h3>
                <p>ES Modules use the modern JavaScript syntax:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>import</code></li>
                    <li><code>export</code></li>
                </ul>
                <p>To enable ES Modules in Node.js, we add <code>"type": "module"</code> in the <code>package.json</code>:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-json">
{
    "type": "module", 
    "dependencies": {
        "express": "^5.2.1"
    }
}
                </code></pre>

                <h4>Exporting with ES Modules</h4>
                <p>There are two types of exports.</p>

                <strong>Named exports</strong>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
export function esModuleCookieFactory() {
    return "On a break...";
}
                </code></pre>
                <strong>Default exports</strong>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
export default {
    esModuleCookieFactory
}
                </code></pre>

                <h4>Importing with ES Modules</h4>
                <strong>Named import</strong>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
import { esModuleCookieFactory } from "./util/esModuleCookiesUtil.js";
                </code></pre>

                <strong>Default exports</strong>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
import cookiesUtil from "./util/esModuleCookiesUtil.js";
                </code></pre>
                
                <h3>Some Pros of Using ES Modules</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>ES Modules is the modern standard way of structuring JavaScript</li>
                    <li>Works in both frontend and backend - the same <code>import</code> / <code>export</code> syntax works in Node.js and in browser scripts</li>
                    <li>Better code organization, which means code can be split into smaller files and reused across a project</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Modules in the Browser</h2>
                <p>
                    JavaScript modules can also be used directly in the browser.
                    To enable this, the script tag must include <code>type="module"</code>.
                </p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-html">
&lt;script type="module" src="./cookies.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
                </code></pre>
                <p>
                    Without <code>type="module"</code>, scripts share the same global scope.
                    This means that variables can accidentally overwrite each other
                    and the order of script loading must be handled manually.
                </p>
                <p>
                    But <strong>with</strong> Modules, every script has its own scope and dependencies are handled automatically.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Redirection</h2>

                <p>
                    Redirection is when a user is sent from one page to another automatically.
                    This can happen either on the client (in the browser) or on the server.
                </p>

                <h3>Client-side Redirection</h3>
                <p>Client-side redirection happens in the browser after a page has already loaded.</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
setTimeout(() => {
    window.location.href = "/";
}, 3000);
                </code></pre>
                <p>Another way is by using a HTML meta tag:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-html">
&lt;meta http-equiv="refresh" content="3; url=/"&gt;
                    </code></pre>

                    <h3>Server-side Redirection</h3>

                    <p>
                        Server-side redirection happens before the page is sent to the browser.
                        Express provides <code>res.redirect()</code> for this.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get("/forecast", (req, res) => {
    res.redirect("/snowstorms");
});
                    </code></pre>

                    <h3>Difference Between Client and Server Redirects</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Client-side redirects happen in the browser after the page loads.</li>
                        <li>Server-side redirects happen on the server before the page loads.</li>
                    </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Reflections (Day 5)</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Serving static files with <code>express.static()</code> is necessary so the browser can access frontend resources like HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.</li>
                    <li>The <code>public</code> folder helps separate client-side files (frontend) from server-side code (backend), which also improves security.</li>
                    <li>Node.js supports two module systems: <code>CommonJS</code> and <code>ES Modules</code>.</li>
                    <li><code>ES Modules</code> use modern <code>import</code> and <code>export</code> syntax and work in both Node.js and the browser.</li>
                    <li>When using modules in the browser, the script must include <code>type="module"</code>.</li>
                    <li>Redirection can happen either on the client (in the browser) or on the server using Express.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
        </div>    
